{<b>Bidding.</b> After North opens 1NT and East passes, South knows the partnership
belongs in a partscore in hearts. Using a <i>Jacoby Transfer</i> bid, South responds
2\D, asking that opener bid 2\H. South now passes to leave the partnership in
its best contract.

<b>Defense.</b> East is on lead and selects the \D10, highest of touching honors. West
should play the \DQ in case East has lead from \DK 10 9.

<b>Declarer play.</b> With the lead of a diamond, North has three sure tricks in
diamonds, but no other sure tricks.

Four tricks in hearts can be promoted, but the lead will have to be lost twice.
Another two tricks can be promoted in clubs. That's plenty of winners. <i>Is there
any problem?</i>

To promote sufficient tricks, the lead must be lost three times. North must
consider the number of tricks that could be lost. Two heart and one club trick
must be lost, and possibly three tricks in spades. That's too many. <i>What
precaution should declarer take?</i>

With the lead of a diamond, North has three winners in diamonds and two <i>extra
winners</i> — winners on which losers can be discarded. North cannot discard enough
losers in clubs to matter, but can discard two losers in spades. Then, the most
North can lose in spades is one trick before being able to ruff.

Discarding immediate losers must be done first. Declarer should play three high
clubs, discarding spades from dummy. Only then can trumps be drawn. Lastly,
North plays on clubs.

<b>Key point.</b> Notice that the 2\H contract might be less successful if played from
South’s side of the table. West might lead the \SQ, trapping North’s \SK. The
defenders could take three spade tricks, two heart tricks and the \DA to defeat
the contract. The transfer bid makes quite a difference to the outcome.

East–West will have difficulty defeating a 2\H contract played from the North
hand. The only winning defense is for East to lead a heart! This hand
illustrates one of the advantages of Jacoby transfer bids. The opening leader
has to choose a lead that plays into the strong hand. This frequently costs the
defense one or more tricks.

South does well to remove partner from the 1NT contract. After a diamond lead
against 1NT, careful defense will restrict North to three diamond tricks and
two club tricks.}
