{<b>Bidding.</b> After South opens 1NT, North uses a Jacoby Transfer bid to request
that partner bid spades. After South accepts the transfer, North raises to 4\S
holding 11 points and knowing that there is at least an 8-card spade fit.

If not playing Jacoby Transfers, North should just respond 4\S.

<b>Defense.</b> South is now declarer and West has the opening lead. The \CQ stands
out. East encourages with the \C8.

<b>Declarer play.</b> South counts six immediate tricks in spades plus one in diamonds
and clubs. There may be a trick in hearts, but the diamond suit looks more
fruitful. Even if the diamond finesse loses, there are at least two more tricks
to be had. <i>Is there any problem?</i>

Check the number of immediate losers. With the club lead, South might lose one
club, one diamond, and two heart tricks if neither the heart or diamond
finesses are working. <i>What what precaution should declarer take?</i>

The trick is to keep East from gaining the lead. Only East can lead through
South's vulnerable \HK. Even if the diamond finesse loses, West cannot lead
hearts to good effect.

South should let West win the \CQ! Then the second round of clubs can be won
with the \CA and a third round ruffed in dummy (if necessary) without East ever
gaining the lead. After pulling trumps, ending in the North hand, declarer runs
the \DJ, losing to the \DK. But, declarer can use dummy's good diamonds to
discard heart losers. In fact, if West does not cash the \HA, she won't get it!

<b>Key point.</b> Although East–West cannot legitimately defeat a contract of 4\H
played by South if declarer is careful, they may get an opportunity. When West
leads the \CQ, East should play the \C8 as an encouraging signal. If declarer
wins the first trick with the \CA, draws trumps, and then takes the diamond
finesse, West can win the \DK and lead a club to East’s \CK. East can finish
off a fine defense by leading the \HQ to trap declarer’s \HK.

If North–South aren’t using transfer bids, East–West will have an excellent
chance to defeat the contract. East would be on lead and could lead the \HQ,
giving the defenders the first two tricks. If they now switch to clubs, they
can take a club trick after declarer loses the finesse to West’s \DK.}
