{<b>Bidding.</b> With an invitational-strength hand and a five-card major suit, South
transfers North to 2\H and then bids 2NT. With a maximum-strength hand for the
1NT opening bid, North has enough to accept the invitation. With the knowledge
that South has five hearts, North puts the partnership in game in the eight-card
fit.

If not playing Jacoby Transfers, South should respond Stayman 2\C, then bid 3\H
(forcing) when North replies 2\S.

<b>Defense.</b> East is on lead and probably will start with the \DJ, highest of
touching honors.

<b>Declarer play.</b> North counts two immediate spade winners, another in diamonds,
and two more in clubs. That leaves North needing to find five more tricks.

Four tricks probably can be promoted in hearts. A finesse of the \CJ is a
possibility for another trick, as is a 3–3 division of spades. Checking
immediate losers. there are only two, the \HA and a diamond, so no worries
there.

Let's say North wins the \DA and tackles trumps, ruffing the third round of
diamonds if necessary. <i>What should declarer play after drawing trumps?</i>

North should next test the spades. A spade must be lost in any event, but then
North's fourth spade is the game-going winner. If spades had not divided 3–3,
only then would North have needed to try the club finesse.

<b>Key point.</b> If declarer tries the club finesse before testing spades, the
contract can be defeated. When the club finesse loses, declarer can end up
losing a trick in every suit. With a choice of plays for extra winners, plays
when both can be attempted, first try the one in which a trick <i>must </i>be lost
(spades), saving for second the one in which a trick <i>might </i>be lost (clubs).

If South–North reach 3NT, rather than 4\H, the defenders have an opportunity to
defeat the contract. East will start with the \DJ, and West must be careful
to play a high diamond on this trick to avoid blocking the suit. If West plays
the two high diamonds early, East–West can get four diamond tricks to go
along with the \HA.}
