{<b>Bidding.</b> After North’s opening 1NT bid, South has a hand for which the best
contract is likely to be a partscore in diamonds. Since a 2\D response would be
a transfer to hearts, South starts by responding 2\S. This asks North to bid 3\C.
South now bids 3\D, a sign-off bid, and North passes.

<b>Defense.</b> West is on lead and probably will lead the \HK. Short but strong
suits are attractive leads against suit contracts (but not against notrump
contracts). East discourages with the \H3 (West might hold only the \HK Q, so
East has no equivalent honor).

<b>Declarer play.</b> South counts just three immediate winners, so needs six more.
Promotion in diamonds will garner four more. Spades will provide two more. A
check of immediate losers reveals only five, two in hearts, two in diamonds,
and probably one in spades. <i>What should declarer do first?</i>

If South first plays on trumps, the defense might take two diamond and two heart
tricks, then play on clubs. Then, when South loses the \SK, the defense will
take two additional tricks in clubs. Spades should be played first.

With no fast entry to take the spade finesse, South just plays the \SA and
another from dummy. If East covers with the \SK, South can ruff and lose no
spade tricks! If East plays low, South can just discard a heart loser. This
type of play is called “discarding a loser on a loser” — if you lose the trick,
you've eliminated a loser anyway, so nothing is lost!

Now, when the defenders play on clubs, South can win the \CA in dummy and
discard two club losers on the established spades.

<b>Key point.</b> When playing Jacoby Transfers, a response of 2\S is used to show a
hand that wants to sign off in 3\C or 3\D. Should have a six-card suit and less
than eight points. An immediate response of 3\C or 3\D is invitational to 3NT,
an 8–9 point hand with a six-card minor.}
